70% reasoning

1. Another source of within-individual variation - can analyze whether low literacy accounts are complements or substitutes 

2. This question is policy relevant - no real-world intervention will be able to mute all low-quality information. Therefore, we need to understand the effects of muting some misinformation accounts on others. 

3. Question on uniform probability of selection versus more complicated weighting approaches

➡️ 70% of the pre-defined list of untrustworthy accounts will be muted

➡️ These 70% will be randomly sampled - but whether to apply weighting or not?

Questions

  • If we simulate 70% sampling(=drawing 70% of the sample 1000 times), how many accounts with large number of follows do we get on average?

  • What is variation in number of follows muted as a proportion of total follows in 1000 draws?

  • How many of top 25 accounts by follows are selected?

Data

  • NG_list: NewsGuard List (the xlsx file from Brendan’s email)

    • This xlsx file is not the version that Brendan sent to Verasight!

    • Accounts that are suspended, doesn’t exist, or with 0 follows are removed

Simulation

Strategy

  1. p(uniform): I randomly choose 70% of the untrustworthy list to mute + iterate this 1000 times

    • Every time I pull 70% (which is 363 accounts out of 519 in the list), my sample will include mix of accounts with higher number of follows and accounts with lower number of follows.

  2. p(weighted): Same as #1 but weighting by # of follows

  3. p(algorithm): custom algorithm that randomly selects accounts to mute from the NG_list until the total number of follows reaches approximately 70% of the total number of follows of all accounts in the list

    • Goal: sample accounts until the total # of follows reaches 70% (± 5%)
    • I randomly sample a chunk of data (n=10) and check if any of the domains already exist in sampled data. If they do, I remove duplicates before appending them to sampled data. In targeting the 70%, I sample in chunks and them remove random rows if necessary, to keep % within the range.
    • Iteration: 1000 times (same!)

In this notebook, I check:

  1. the variation in mean # of follows of muted accounts

  2. the variation in median # of follows of muted accounts

  3. the variation in # of follows of muted accounts (70%) / total # of follows across accounts (=100%)

  4. the variation of counts of top 25 accounts by follows

# backup 
df <- NG_list

# Set seed so that the random sampling is consistent every time I run the script
set.seed(123)

iterations <- 1000  # Number of times to repeat the sampling process
sample_size <- floor(0.7 * nrow(df))  # Size of each sample, which is 70% of total rows in df
#*********************** Set up ***********************#
# Top 25 accounts by follows in the untrustworthy list: 
top_accounts <- df |>              
  arrange(desc(followers)) |>       
  slice(1:25) |>                    
  pull(domain)                

# Create empty vectors to hold results: 
mean_followers <- numeric(iterations)     # Mean of # of followers in 70% 
median_followers <- numeric(iterations)   # Median 
prop_total_follows_muted <- numeric(iterations)   
top_accounts_selected_count <- integer(iterations)

for (i in seq_len(iterations)) {  
  # Randomly select 70% without replacement
  sample_df <- df |> 
    sample_n(size = sample_size, replace = FALSE)   
  
  # Calculate mean followers in this sample 
  mean_followers[i] <- mean(sample_df$followers)
  
  # Calculate median followers in this sample 
  median_followers[i] <- median(sample_df$followers)

  # Calculate proportion of total follows muted 
  prop_total_follows_muted[i] <- sum(sample_df$followers) / sum(df$followers)    
  
  # Count how many selected domains are among top accounts
  top_accounts_selected_count[i] <- sum(sample_df$domain %in% top_accounts)         
}

# Set quantile range: 
quantile_range = c(0, 0.025, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, .975, 1)

Example of 70% sample:

datatable(sample_df, caption = "Example of 70% sample")

list(

  "Mean follows"=quantile(mean_followers , quantile_range),
  ## Get specified quantiles for median followers distribution   
  "Median follows"=quantile(median_followers , quantile_range),
  ## Get specified quantiles for proportion of total follows muted
  "Proportion of follows muted" = quantile(prop_total_follows_muted , quantile_range),   
  ## Get specified quantiles for count of top accounts selected 
  "Top 25 accounts count"= quantile(top_accounts_selected_count , quantile_range)
  ) -> results

3. p(algorithm)

What does this custom algorithm do?

  1. For each iteration, it initializes an empty data frame `sample_df` to store the sampled data.
  1. Then it enters a loop where it randomly samples a chunk (n=20; can be changed) at a time from the NG_list.
  1. This process continues until the total number of followers across all accounts in `sample_df` lies within the range around 70% (±5%) of total followers across all accounts in the NG_list.

Please note that this algorithm ensures there is no duplicates within `sample_df`; it checks whether randomly drawn account (represented by its domain) in each chunk is already present in `sample_df`. If yes, then this duplicate is discarded.

※ But using this algorithm would result in different number of muted accounts per user.

set.seed(123)
# Number of iterations
iterations <- 1000

# Calculate total followers, target, lower_bound, upper_bound
total_followers <- sum(df$followers)
target <- total_followers * 0.7
lower_bound <- target * 0.95
upper_bound <- target * 1.05

chunk_size <- 20 # Define your chunk size here 

# Preallocate vectors to store results from each iteration
mean_followers = numeric(iterations)
median_followers = numeric(iterations)
prop_total_follows_muted = numeric(iterations)
top_25_accounts_included_count = integer(iterations)

# Get top 25 accounts by follower count
top_25_accounts <- df %>% 
    top_n(25,followers) %>% 
    pull(domain)

for(i in seq_len(iterations)){
    # Initialize an empty DataFrame for your sample 
    sample_df=data.frame()

    while(nrow(sample_df)==0 | sum(sample_df$followers) < lower_bound){
        temp_sample=df[sample(nrow(df), chunk_size),]
        # Check if domains in temp_sample already exist in sample_df. If they do, remove them from temp_sample.
        if (nrow(sample_df) > 0){
            temp_sample = temp_sample[!(temp_sample$domain %in% sample_df$domain),]
        }
        sample_df=rbind(sample_df,temp_sample)
    }

    while(sum(sample_df$followers) > upper_bound){
        # If sum of followers is above upper bound after adding a chunk,
        # remove random rows until it's within bounds.
        drop_indices=sample(seq_len(nrow(sample_df)),1)
        sample_df=sample_df[-drop_indices,]
    }

    mean_followers[i]=mean(sample_df$followers)
    median_followers[i]=median(sample_df$followers)
    prop_total_follows_muted[i]=(sum(sample_df$followers)/total_followers)
    top_25_accounts_included_count[i]=sum(sapply(unique(as.character(sample_df$domain)), function(x) x %in% top_25_accounts))
}


quantile_range =c(0.0, .025,.25,.5,.75,.975 ,1)
results=list(
'Mean follows' = quantile(mean_followers , quantile_range),
'Median follows' = quantile(median_followers , quantile_range),
'Proportion follows muted'= quantile(prop_total_follows_muted , quantile_range),   
'Top accounts count'=quantile(top_25_accounts_included_count ,quantile_range))

# Convert the list as dataframe: 
df_results_algorithm <- as.data.frame(t(do.call(rbind, results)))

options(scipen=999)

df_results_algorithm <- df_results_algorithm %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, function(x){round(x, digits=3)})

rownames(df_results_algorithm) <- c("Min", "P2.5", "P25", "Median", "P75", "P97.5", "Max")

datatable(df_results_algorithm)
